Access Token (JWT)

Purpose: Used to authorize the user for accessing protected APIs.
It is sent with every request and usually contains user identity and permissions/roles.
Expiry: Short-lived (e.g., 10–30 minutes).

Access token is send with each API call so it travels a lot so there is chances of leak, and if get accessed by attackers then min damage

Refresh Token
Purpose: Used to generate a new access token when the current access token expires, allowing the user to stay logged in without re-authentication.
It is stored securely and is not used to access APIs directly.
Expiry: Long-lived (e.g., 7–30 days).




✅ Authentication
Meaning: Verifying who you are.
It checks user identity (login).
📌 Example:
Logging in using email/password, OTP, Google login.
➡️ Output: "Yes, this is Kuldeep."

✅ Authorization

Meaning: Verifying what you are allowed to do.
It checks permissions/roles after login.
📌 Example:
Can user access admin dashboard?
Can student submit assignment?
Can teacher edit marks?
➡️ Output: "Kuldeep can access this page / cannot access this page."